E. angustifolia
has been identified as having numerous ethnobotanical uses by the local people of Turkey and is a potential herbal medicine for the treatment of diabetes mellitus (DM). The decoction of its leaves is consumed as a blood glucose-lowering agent (
) while the infusions from its flowers and leaves are consumed as diuretics and antipyretics (
). Previous studies have shown that
E. angustifolia
exerts antiarthritic, anti-inflammatory, antimicrobial, antimutagenic, antinociceptive, antioxidant, antitumor, cardioprotective, gastroprotective, hypolipidemic, insecticidal, tyrosinase inhibitory, and wound-healing effects (
;
). The in vitro α -glucosidase and α -amylase inhibitory effects of the 70% methanol extract prepared from the leaves of
E. angustifolia
have been evaluated using different methods. However, to the best of our knowledge, further studies have not been conducted to determine the effective compounds in the extract (
). By investigating the hypoglycemic effect of polysaccharides obtained from the fruit of this plant, a previous study found that these polysaccharides could potently prevent increased levels of glucose in streptozotocin-induced diabetic mice compared to control mice (
). Angustifolinoid B, which is obtained from the flowers, was also found to exhibit strong α -glucosidase inhibitory activity (
). Specialized metabolites, such as β -carboline alkaloids, esters, flavone glycosides, ketones, phenolic acids, phenols, phenyl ethers, polysaccharides, steroids, and terpenes, have also been identified previously in
E. angustifolia ( Farzaei et al., 2015 )
.

DM is an endocrine disease characterized by hyperglycemia. This condition is also associated with deficient or excess insulin secretion induced by irregularities in carbohydrate, fat, and protein metabolism. Approximately 85–95% of people with DM have type II DM, which is a chronic metabolic disease caused by the inability of the body to secrete sufficient insulin or the development of insulin resistance (
;
). Defects in α -amylase, α -glucosidase, aldose reductase, angiotensin-converting enzyme, and dipeptidyl peptidase-4 play a role in the pathogenesis of type II DM (
). Drugs used in a clinical setting to control DM include insulin, sulfonylureas, biguanides, thiazolidinediones, carbamoylmethyl benzoic acid, insulin-like growth factor, aldose reductase-, α -glucosidase-, and α -amylase inhibitors (
;
;
). In addition to using these drugs for the treatment of type II DM, other therapeutic approaches, such as inhibiting the degradation of oligosaccharides and disaccharides, can be used to reduce hyperglycemia.
α -
Glucosidase and
α -
amylase can hydrolyze carbohydrates; thus, inhibitors of these enzymes are considered useful drug candidates for type II DM therapy (
;
;
). Inhibitors of
α -
glucosidase and
α -
amylase delay carbohydrate digestion, thereby prolonging carbohydrate digestion time and decreasing glucose absorption rate, which lead to an decrease in postprandial plasma glucose (
). Long-term use of synthetic enzyme inhibitors, such as acarbose, may cause various side effects, such as flatulence and abdominal problems (
). Natural
α -
glucosidase inhibitors have thus been presented as a better alternative to control postprandial hyperglycemia as they exhibit minor or no side effects (
).

