Compound 1 ( trans -tiliroside) showed high α -glucosidase inhibition, whereas compound 7 (astragalin) had no effect ( Table 3 , Fig. 3 ). Although both compounds have a kaempferol unit, the effect exhibited by compound 1 could be attributed to the linkage of trans -coumaroyl with the C-6 of glucose (
). Such findings are supported by those of
. The anti-glycation effect of trans --tiliroside, the major compound of
E. angustifolia
flowers, was previously evaluated. Aminoguanidine (the comparative standard) displayed an anti-glycation effect of 55.3%, while 37.5 μg/mL of trans -tiliroside displayed an effect of 78.9% (
). trans -Tiliroside has also been isolated from
Potentilla chinensis
and
Allium cepa
and its hypoglycemic effect has been determined. Accordingly, a significant anti-hyperglycemic effect was identified based on the reduction in blood glucose in diabetic rats (
;
).

Consistent with the results of the α -glucosidase enzyme-inhibition assay, compound 1 ( trans -tiliroside) was found to be most effective in scavenging ABTS radicals ( Table 3 , Fig. 6 ), likely owing to the presence of kaempferol and trans -coumaric acid in its structure ( Fig. 1 ). Methoxylation of the B ring was found to decrease this effect, whereas the presence of phenolic acid in the structure increased the effect (
). trans -Tiliroside ( 1 ) was previously shown to possess exhibit ABTS radical-scavenging activity, but was found to be ineffective in scavenging DPPH radicals, as observed in our study (
).

