, with slight modifications (
). All samples (20 μL), enzyme solution (10 μL, 1 U/mL), and potassium phosphate buffer (50 μL, 50 mM, pH 6.9) were mixed in a 96-well plate and incubated at 37 ◦ C for 5 min. To initiate the reaction, the substrate, p -nitrophenyl- α -D-glucopyranoside (20 μL, 3 mM), was added to each well. The mixtures were subsequently incubated at 37 ◦ C for 30 min. Thereafter, to quench the reaction, 0.1 M sodium carbonate (50 μL) was added to each well. Acarbose was used as a positive control. The amount of p -nitrophenol was measured using a 96-well microplate reader at 405 nm . Each assay was performed in triplicate for all samples. The percentage inhibition of all samples was calculated using the following equation:

The inhibitory effect on α -amylase was determined according to the method of
, with slight modifications (
). All samples (100 μL) and 1% starch solution (100 μL) in 20 mM sodium phosphate buffer (pH 6.9 containing 6 mM sodium chloride) were incubated at 25 ◦ C for 10 min in a 24-well microplate. After incubation, 100 μL α -amylase solution ( 0.5 mg /mL) was added to each well and the reaction mixtures were incubated at 25 ◦ C for 10 min. The reaction was subsequently terminated by the addition of dinitrosalicylic acid color reagent (200 μL). After the microplate was heated in a boiling water bath for 5 min and cooled to 25 ◦ C, 50 μL was removed from each well and transferred to a 96-well microplate. The reaction mixture was diluted by the addition of 200 μL distilled water, and the absorbance at 540 nm was measured. Acarbose was used as the positive control. Each assay was performed in triplicate for all samples. The percentage inhibition of all samples was calculated using the following equation:
